Kenosha Public Market is a year-round Saturday market located in the heart of the Downtown district. Our vendors present a variety of products including local produce, artisan pastries and confections, locally sourced meats, poultry and eggs, fine cheeses, prepared foods & handmade gifts. Order from our online store, KPM2GO, to ensure you get the products you want before they sell out. Place orders during the week and pick up at our Saturday market! _x000d_
Our location is in the center of this pedestrian-friendly neighborhood with convenient parking options, world-class museums, an authentic streetcar system, two lighthouses, unique dining, and plenty of shopping options. Kenosha Public Market is proud to be one of the many shopping destinations Downtown.

listing_desc: Established in 2023, the Fort Morgan Farmers Market honors the rich agricultural heritage of Northeast Colorado. It offers food business owners a reliable platform to connect with customers throughout the warm growing season, while creating a welcoming gathering place for the community. The market also opens its doors to local artists and organizations, adding even more color and connection to the experience! Every market is hosted at The Block, a shared kitchen and community center, come by and take a walk around The Block!

This leisurely market is a grass roots effort to promote healthy foods and clean products for people who are searching for a healthier lifestyle. Vegetables are grown using natural methods, no synthetic fertilizers or pesticides. Meats are from pastured pigs, goats and cattle. Raw, Wildflower honey and the natural health and beauty products made from bee products are from a hive close to the market center. The majority of businesses sell foods, a handful of businesses sell handmade items. One Tupperware business promotes products that preserve freshness and that promotes reusing containers. This market runs for 9 months. The market hosts business professionals with high quality standards and customer driven engagement through an informal board and a volunteer facilitator. All potential food businesses are directed to the Bell County Health Department for proper licensing and an understanding of the law. Businesses are directed to the State for necessary business licensing.

location_desc: Ann Arbor Farmers Market is located in the heart of the Kerrytown District within the City of Ann Arbor. There is street parking available adjacent to the market on Detroit Street. We are 4 blocks from the Blake Transit station and there are multiple parking lots as well as street parking available within walking distance.
listing_desc: Founded in 1919, and operating from our current location since 1930, our 106 year old market is the second oldest continuously operating public market in the state of Michigan. As a producer-only market, all 130 of our vendors are the grower, producer, or maker of the products that they sell. Ann Arbor Farmers Market is also open twice daily in May-December, and on Saturdays year-round. We accept 5 different food assistance programs, and have the highest amount of food assistance dollars spent at our market as compared to other farmers markets in Washtenaw County. We host special events like Cooking Demos, Food Truck Rallies, and Flower Day, and have prepared food, live music, and community groups regularly throughout our market season. We are run by the the City of Ann Arbor Parks and Recreation Department. As we are a City park, others rent our space for events like the Sunday Artisan Market, Kindlefest, Ann Arbor Asian Night Market, The Local Food Festival, and more.

It is open on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 12 p.m. to 5 p.m. and on Saturdays from 1 p.m. to 5 p.m. We open later in the day to allow the farmers to bring only the freshest produce, picked that morning, to the market. The Market welcomes only Wisconsin-based growers and makers, so you can shop local and enjoy the best Wisconsin has to offer. The West Allis Farmers Market is an open-air, European style market that has been operating since 1919.

listing_desc: Millen Produce Market is your local destination for fresh, homemade, and homegrown goodness right in the heart of our community. Each week, you’ll find an abundance of farm-fresh vegetables picked at their peak. From juicy tomatoes and crisp cucumbers to seasonal favorites like squash, okra, and sweet corn, our farmers bring the very best of the garden straight to you. Alongside produce, the market showcases a variety of homemade goods made with care and tradition. Local kitchens stock tables with delicious baked treats—cakes, cookies, breads, and pies—that capture the warmth of home cooking. For those who love classic Southern flavors, shelves of jams, jellies, and preserves are filled with the tastes of summer in a jar, ready to sweeten your mornings or make the perfect gift. No visit would be complete without sampling Georgia’s favorite snack—hot, salty boiled peanuts. Freshly cooked and seasoned, they’re the perfect companion while you browse the market.

listing_desc:
This neighborhood farmers market is located at Old MacDonald’s Farm, a City-owned and operated petting farm open seasonally. The market is open on Wednesdays, from 4-6 p.m., June through September. Vendors lease stalls from the City to sell fruits, vegetables, meats, and crafts to local consumers. _x000d_

Our community farmers market is more than just a place to shop—it’s a place to connect. What makes our market truly special is the meaningful relationship it fosters between local farmers, makers, artisans, and the community. Shoppers get to meet the people behind the products, hear their stories, and learn where and how their food and goods are made. We proudly support local producers by offering a welcoming space to share their fresh produce, locally raised meats, eggs, honey, freshly baked goods, canned goods, all-natural bath and body care, wellness products, and more. Every visit promotes a healthier lifestyle and a stronger local economy, all while building trust, transparency, and community spirit. At our market, you're not just buying local—you're building relationships that matter.
